Categorical Data Analysis

  • What is categorical data?

“A categorical variable has a measurement scale consisting of a set of categories”

Agresti (2002, 1)

“We live in a categorical world! From a positive or negative disease diagnosis to choosing all items that apply in a survey, outcomes are frequently organized into categories so that people can more easily make sense of them”

Bilder and Loughin (2014, ix)

“In statistics, a categorical variable is a variable that can take on one of a limited, and usually fixed number of possible values, assigning each individual or other unit of observation to a particular group or nominal category on the basis of some qualitative property.”

(Wikipedia entry for Categorical variable, accessed on the 20-Oct-2019)

Categorical Data Analysis II

So it seems categorical data analysis is defined by the type of data…

  • Discrete v. Continuous
  • In R: float, numeric, factor, logical, character types

A well known hierarchy (though controversial) of variable types goes something like this:

  1. Qualitative information
  2. Binary and nominal
  3. Ordinal
  4. Discrete or count
  5. Interval
  6. Ratio

Content of this Seminar

  • Introduction to using R: functions and packages for categorical data (e.g. tidyverse for data cleaning and management)
  • But what is a categorical variable anyway: Latent versus observed variables
  • Uni-dimensional measures of association
  • Multivariate methods: the general linear regression model and friends
  • Ordinal data is everywhere
  • Prediction problems: supervised and unsupervised context
  • Summarizing results: statistics and in Tables or in Figures (plots with ggplot2)
